Eventually they succeed and the grateful girl finally returns the love of the engineer."|~|Tagline: "A Spanish beauty,---a Yankee hero---a story of revolution and adventure without a dull moment---See 'The Adventurer'"

Title: Dennis O'Keefe and Helen Walker in Her Adventurous Night
Description.caption: Text from back of photo: She Meant No Harm. Dennis O'Keefe and Helen Walker are paired romantically in "She Meant No Harm," rollicking comedy about a telephone trouble-shooter who picks up a girl bound for the altar with another man. Before the final reel, Dennis changes Helen's mind about marrying the other fellow. Crisp dialogue adds to this Universal film's gay mood.
Description.note: Film was originally titled She Meant No Harm.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Lionel Barrymore in It's a Wonderful Life
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A modern Scrooge in the person of the town banker, Mr. Potter, is the top featured role played by veteran Lionel Barrymore in Liberty Films' initial production, Frank Capra's "It's a Wonderful Life," which stars James Stewart and Donna Reed. Barrymore won the Academy Award for best performance by an actor in 1931 for his work in "A Free Soul."

Title: Paul Douglas and Ruth Roman in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Death Dealer - Lily Macbeth (Ruth Roman) gives her husband Joe (Paul Douglas) the knife with which he is to murder his gang chief in this thrilling moment in the Mike Frankovich production, Joe Macbeth, for Columbia.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas and Ruth Roman in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Murderer's Mistake - Ruth Roman learns from her husband Paul Douglas that he has left the incriminating knife in his gang boss's body in this scene from Mike Frankovich's Joe Macbeth, for Columbia.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas, Al Mulock, and George Marco in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Paul Douglas is enraged when his two assassins Al Mulock and George Margo, mistakenly murder a fellow gangster's family in this scene from Mike Frankovich's Joe Macbeth for Columbia. Ruth Roman co-stars with Douglas.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas and Harry Green in Joe Macbeth
Description.caption: Text from the back of photograph: Friendly Rivals - Big Dutch (Harry Green) chats with Joe Macbeth (Paul Douglas) in this night club scene from producer Mike Frankovich's action thriller, Joe Macbeth, for Columbia. Ruth Roman co-stars as Lily Macbeth.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas, Sidney James, and Gregoire Aslan in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Bonus - Paul Douglas receives a diamond ring as bonus from gang chief Gregoire Aslan. Sidney James adds his congratulations, in this scene from Mike Frankovich's action thriller, Joe Macbeth, for Columbia. Ruth Roman co-stars with Douglas.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas and Harry Green in Joe Macbeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Rival Mobsters - Paul Douglas pays a strictly unfriendly call on Harry Green in this scene from producer Mike Frankovich's Joe Macbeth, for Columbia. Paul Douglas plays title role and Ruth Roman co-stars.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas and Ruth Roman in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Nightmare - Ruth Roman is comforted by her husband Paul Douglas, when she dreams there is blood on her hands in this scene from Mike Frankovich's thriller, Joe Macbeth, for Columbia.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Paul Douglas, Sidney James, and Kay Callard in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Gang Victim - Kay Callard opens the door for Sidney James and Paul Douglas. Douglas has been wounded in a gang fight, in this scene from Mike Frankovich's Joe Macbeth, for Columbia. Ruth Roman co-stars with Douglas.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Ruth Roman and other unidentified cast members in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Hostess with the Mostest - Ruth Roman throws a big housewarming party for gangster chief king pin Gregoire Aslan and his mobsters. Her husband Paul Douglas is the king's No. 1 boy. Mike Frankovich produced the action thriller, Joe Macbeth, for Columbia.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Bonar Colleano and other unidentified cast members in Joe MacBeth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Bonar Colleano in Joe Macbeth, Columbia-British 1950.

Title: David Bruce, Barbara Bates, and Jean Trent in Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: David Bruce appears quite embarrassed by all the attention he's getting from Barbara Bates (L) and Jean Trent while all three wait to be called before the cameras for a scene in the Circus Club set of Deanna Durbin's current Universal comedy-mystery, Lady on a Train.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Director Charles David, producer Felix Jackson, and actress Deanna Durbin on the set of Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Winter invaded one of the huge sound stages at Universal Studio for one of the sequences in Deanna Durbin's new comedy-mystery, Lady on a Train. And here Director Charles David (L) and Producer Felix Jackson are trying to convince Deanna that it really is cold.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Deanna Durbin, David Bruce, and his wife Cynthia on the set of Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Deanna Durbin invites David Bruce and his wife Cynthia, into the trailer that she uses as a portable dressing room during production of her current Universal comedy-mystery, Lady n a Train.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: The original writer of Lady on a Train, author Leslie Charteris and his wife
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Leslie Charteris, popular mystery writer and creator of the famous Saint series, and his wife, the former Betty Bryant, singer. Charteris wrote the original story for Deanna Durbin's current Universal picture, Lady on a Train.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Deanna Durbin, another unidentified cast member, and extras in Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Lady on a Train w/ Deanna Durbin

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Deanna Durbin and other unidentified actors in Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Deanna Durbin in Lady on a Train, Universal 1945.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Deanna Durbin and crew members in Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: With three members of the crew holding a ladder, Deanna Durbin perches on top of a high iron fence preparatory to shooting a scene for her Universal comedy-mystery, Lady on a Train.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Deanna Durbin and crew members in Lady on a Train
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Deanna Durbin watches from behind the camera with script girl Mary Chaffee and director Charles David, during the filming of a scene in which she doesn't appear in her new Universal comedy-mystery, Lady on a Train.

Title: Lizabeth Scott on the set of Paid In Full

Description.note: Although the caption lists the film as "Bitter Victory," that was the working title. It was released as "Paid in Full."

(PLEASE CREDIT "BITTER VICTORY").Still #2/181, 2/179, 2/182, 2/184

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Jane Russell in The Paleface
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: As Calamity Jane in Paramount's The Paleface, lovely Jane Russell makes her screen debut opposite of Bob Hope as a romantic comedienne --- a radical change from her two previous screen appearances and one that serves to introduce the talented star's capabilities as an actress to theater audience. She plays a bad girl with a big heart role in the laugh-provoking travesty on Wild West thrillers.

Title: Franciska Gaal in promotional material for Paris Honeymoon
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:POSTER BECOMES MODEL--The Balkan wedding gown worn by Franciska Gaal in Paramount's "Paris Honeymoon," was designed from a poster picked up by Producer-Harlan Thompson in Hungary several years ago. While the entire wardrobe department and Thompson's staff were wracking their brains to get some original and yet authentic design for the wedding gown, the producer remembered the poster. He seized upon it immediately for the design. Curiously, Miss Gaal, a Hungarian, strikingly resembles the girls on the poster.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Poster art for George Marshall's The Perils Of Pauline
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:REMEMBER WHEN?---Gaudy posters like this used to be displayed in front of the nickelodeons to herald another hair-raising episode in the silent flicker serial, "The Perils of Pauline," with the invincible Pearl White again facing death and destruction by every imaginable lethal device before she was saved in the nick of time for next week's installment. The early day movie lithographs picturing the peerless Pauline enduring all the horrors and tortures concocted by the black-hearted villain were reproduced for the new Paramount Technicolor feature with the original serial title. Betty Hutton plays the dauntless heroine of the cliffhanging thrillers which kept the Friday night Bijou patrons on the edge of their seats through an endless succession of breath-taking adventures. John Lund is the handsome hero and the Blonde Bombshell's co-star in the film, directed by George Marshall, which is certain to invoke many a nostalgic memory.(PLEASE CREDIT "THE PERILS OF PAULINE")|~|VALLEY of DOOMEPISODE 4

Title: Ella Raines and Alan Curtis in Phantom Lady
Description.caption: "PHANTOM LADY""Phantom Lady," a tense mystery drama, is a Universal production starring Franchot Tone, Ella Raines and Alan Curtis, directed by Robert Siodmak with Joan Harrison as associate producer. It is the story of a young man unjustly condemned to die for the murder of his wife, of the despairing efforts of the girl who loves him to locate the "phantom" witness who can establish his innocence, and of the mad machinations of the real criminal in seeking to save himself from exposure.6. Convicted by a jury which refused to believe his unsupported alibi, Scott is sentenced to be executed. In prison he is visited by his former secretary, Carol Richman (ELLA RAINES), turns deaf ears on her urgings that he appeal.From: Universal Studios,Universal City, Calif."Phantom Lady," a tense mystery drama, is a Universal production starring Franchot Tone, Ella Raines and Alan Curtis, directed by Robert Siodmak with Joan Harrison as associate producer. It is the story of a young man unjustly condemned to die for the murder of his wife, of the despairing efforts of the girl who loves him to locate the "phantom" witness who can establish his innocence, and of the mad machinations of the real criminal in seeking to save himself from exposure.6. Convicted by a jury which refused to believe his unsupported alibi, Scott is sentenced to be executed. In prison he is visited by his former secretary, Carol Richman (ELLA RAINES), turns deaf ears on her urgings that he appeal.

Title: Nelson Eddy and Jane Farrar in Phantom Of The Opera
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:TWO SINGING STARS FROM "PHANTOM OF THE OPERA"Nelson Eddy's drolleries cause an unscheduled emotion to creep into the dramatic performance of Jane Farrar as the couple pose for gallery portraits at Universal where they acted and sang together in the Technicolor "Phantom of the Opera". Originally, the pose was to be one of romantic ardor, but a moment before the still photographer could press his shutter, Mr. Eddy uttered a wise crack, causing Miss Farrar to "break up" with laughter.From: Universal Studios,Universal City, Calif.Nelson Eddy's drolleries cause an unscheduled emotion to creep into the dramatic performance of Jane Farrar as the couple pose for gallery portraits at Universal where they acted and sang together in the Technicolor "Phantom of the Opera". Originally, the pose was to be one of romantic ardor, but a moment before the still photographer could press his shutter, Mr. Eddy uttered a wise crack, causing Miss Farrar to "break up" with laughter.

Title: Deborah Kerr in Please Believe Me
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:M-G-M PICTORIAL PREVIEW......."PLEASE BELIEVE ME"1. "WEALTHY" HEIRESS: Alison Kirbe (Deborah Kerr), a pretty English girl, inherits a 50,000 acre ranch from her dear old American friend, Hank Wedburn, who died at his home in Texas. Alison's inheritance is much publicized and she leaves for America not knowing her friend's glowing description of his land was much exaggerated, and was, in fact, not worth much more than 10 cents and acre.

Title: Elizabeth Flournoy, Kathleen Lockhart, Ivis Goulding, Barry Jones, Keith McConnell, and others in rehearsal for Plymouth Adventure
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:REHEARSAL...by studio voice coach Arthur Rosenstein gets concentrated attention of the cast. Left to right: Elizabeth Flournoy, Kathleen Lockhart, Ivis Goulding, Barry Jones, Keith McConnell, Van Johnson, Leo Genn, Gene Tierney, Dawn Addams and Murray Matheson."Plymouth Adventure" is M-G-M's exciting and dramatic story of the Mayflower's voyage in 1620 -- what happened to the 102 passengers and 33 sailors, cooped up aboard a 90-foot ship for 66 days. Produced in Technicolor by Dore Schary and directed by Clarence Brown from the Helen Deutsch screen play, "Plymouth Adventure" has an outstanding cast headed by Spencer Tracy, Gene Tierney, Van Johnson, Leo Genn, Dawn Addams, Barry Jones and other top-flight stars of Hollywood, New York and London.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Elaine Shepard in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Picks Perfect Cleopatra-- Harold Lloyd in casting for the role of an Egyptian beauty in his new comedy, Professor, Beware!, picked Elaine Shepard out of over 100 candidates as the perfect modern Cleopatra. Miss Shepard, a former photographer's model, has of late had considerable screen opportunity.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Phyllis Welch and crew members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Once Over Lightly Before the Scene is Shot-- Charlie Dudley adds finishing touches to the makeup of Phyllis Welch, shown here on location preparing for a sequence in Professor, Beware!, Harold Lloyd's current screen offering.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Refuge in a Refrigerator Car- escaping from police, Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch, as an archeologist and his girl, seek refuge in a refrigerator car, but are locked in and almost frozen before they are rescued. It's a scene from Professor, Beware!, Lloyd's new comedy for Paramount release.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and another cast member in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Sailor, Beware! - Harold Lloyd, as a bashful archeologist in his current comedy, Professor, Beware!, engages in a hand-to-hand struggle with sailors. In this picture Lloyd returns to his familiar style of fast action comedy and gags.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Lionel Stander, and Raymond Walburn in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Dispute in a Cattle Car -- Harold Lloyd, in company with hoboes Lionel Stander and Raymond Walburn, gets into an argument and is almost kicked out of the moving car. However, Walburn intercedes in his favor in this riotous scene from Professor, Beware!.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Even a Comedian Appears Sad - when in a predicament like this. Harold Lloyd, as an archeologist who tries to get to New York by stowing away in a refrigerator car with the temperature at 15 degrees, has many hilarious moments in his new comedy, Professor, Beware! The ice coating is partly real frost, but is furthered by the application of Hollywood's own recipe for frost.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Lionel Stander, Raymond Walburn, and Thurston Hall in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: The Professor Plays Too Rough - Harold Lloyd, backed up by Raymond Walburn and Lionel Stander, as a pair of hobos, gots[sic] into a free-for-all battle on the New York docks. Lloyd, in Professor, Beware!, is seen in a typical role as an archeologist who is constantly in hot water.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Lionel Stander in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea-- 7. The games goes on. Lloyd and Stander have inaugurated a series of backgammon contests which carry on through-out the entire production. The afterdeck of the Jasmine forms a pleasant setting.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and another cast member in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Lloyd Plays Rough -- A brawl with sailors who are attempting to throw him from a yacht is one of the action highlights in Professor, Beware!, to be released under Paramount banner. Lloyd's new picture returns in pots to his earlier thrill-a-minute style.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: September Morn - as an innocent victim of circumstances, Harold Lloyd gets into a typical predicament in this scene from Professor, Beware! The comedian, a dignified and conservative professor of archeology, loans his clothes to a needy drunk, and is promptly nabbed by the law on a charge of indecent exposure.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Sterling Holloway in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: There's a Laugh a Minute -- when two comedians hold conversation. Harold Lloyd and Sterling Holloway, both appearing in Lloyd's current production of Professor, Beware!, swap anecdotes while resting between scenes.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Sterling Holloway, and Mary Lou Lender in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Aren't You Ashamed of Yourself--- Harold Lloyd, in this scene from Professor, Beware!, is discovered as a stowaway in a honeymoon trailer by the newlyweds themselves, played by Mary Lou Lender and Sterling Holloway. Lloyd is an archeologist trying to reach New York to join and Egyptian expedition.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Romance at the Age of 70 -- Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch are seen briefly in a tag ending for Professor, Beware! as an elderly couple still very much in love. Lloyd plays an archeologist whose chief ambition is to discover and translate a fragment of an ancient Egyptian tablet.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, James Donlan, and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Immodest Egyptologist -- Harold Lloyd, as an innocent archeologist in Professor, Beware!, becomes a victim of circumstances. Recognized by a prowling reporter (James Donlan), Lloyd, as Professor Lambert, makes newspaper headlines as a Jekyl-and-Hyde character, loses his job, and is thus thrown into a thousand amusing situations.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From Small Beginnings-- Many of the cinema's brightest stars of today had obscure beginnings. Some few have leaped at once into prominence. The roles of nearly all have varied from picture to picture. It is quite a contrast to consider first roles and present ones of the players in question. Memories are reawakened in many instances of pictures of yesteryear, and of some personalities long forgotten. 2) More than over tops in the field of thrills, Harold Lloyd packs many spine-tinglers in his latest picture Professor, Beware!, together with numerous comedy quirks. Here is one scene from his new picture. Harold's in trouble, as might be expected.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus -- 7. Blissfully unconscious of the furor he has created the Professor (lloyd) lies motionless in the sarcophagus of Neferus. His over-zealous attempt to experiment has resulted in near-calamity.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Dewey Robinson in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Dunking a Comedian-- 4. No Lloyd sequence is complete without a few gags and Professor, Beware!, allows no exceptions. After coming out of the water, Lloyd induces waterfront characters to chase him by means of a few well-timed insults. Here he is seen just before pouring a glass of lemonade down Dewey Robinson's trousers.

Name.actor: Lane, Charles|~|Lloyd, Harold, $d 1893-1971|~|Rub, Christian, $d 1886-1956|~|Donlan, James, $d 1888-1938|~|Love, Montagu, $d 1877-1943
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, James Donlan, Christian Rub, Montagu Love, and Charles Lane in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Buried Alive in a Mummy-Case -- much of the action in Harold Lloyd's current comedy, Professor, Beware!, takes place in a museum, where the comedian, as an ambitious archeologist, is conducting an experiment to determine whether or not a person could live while sealed up in a sarcophagus. He almost suffocates, but is rescued by the Museum directo, played by Montagu Love (upper left), an attendent, played by Chrisian Rub (lower right), and two reporters, James Donlan (lower left) and Charles Lane.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Gag in an Ancient Coffin - Harold Lloyd, as an enterprising archeologist in Professor, Beware!, proves that a person can live while entombed in an Egyptian sarcophagus. The comedian can't resist gagging a wink, even in the gloom of the interior of a coffin.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Mirrored in Harbor Waters - Harold Lloyd, apparently carrying on a conversation with his reflection in the water, is in reality rehearsing for a scene in his new Paramount release, Professor, Beware! The comedian must fall into the water and swim to a yacht anchored nearby. The scene was shot in icy January weather, and was just one of many uncomfortable moments for Lloyd during production.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Embarrassing Moment #5, 280- snapped by news photographers after having been hauled into jail on mistaken charges of indecent exposure, Harold Lloyd, as a [sedate?] young Egyptologist, endeavors to preserve a semblance of dignity in this scene from Professor, Beware!

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and crew members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus -- 2. Here Lloyd is shown being assisted by prop men to make himself comfortable during his extended stay in the gloomy interior of the sarcophagus.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Dr. John A. Comstock preparing props for Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd Goes Egyptian -- 3. Lloyd, in his character as an Egyptologist, goes in for authentic detail. Above he is seen with Dr. John A. Comstock, a director in the Los Angeles Museum, who is comparing the tablets with a real one in the showcase.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Lionel Stander in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Fun in a Cattle Car - Harold Lloyd, in this exciting sequence from Professor, Beware!, is ably seconded by Lionel Stander (left rear) and Raymond Walburm. When cameras actually start to grind, the board upon which the comedian is resting will be removed, and the scene will show him hanging from the ceiling. Trouble with unruly steers made this one of the most difficult shots in the picture to make.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and composer Harry Owens off the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Composer Autographs New Hit - Harry Owens, whose Sweet Leilani, won the Motion Picture Academy award as the best film song of 1937, autographs his new hit tune, Cocoanut[sic] Grove, for Harold Lloyd. Owens and his Royal Hawaiian Orchestra from Honolulu were specially imported by Paramount to appear in the filmusical[sic], Cocoanut Grove, for which the maestro has written the music.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Lure of the Nile-- Harold Lloyd, who plays the part of an archeologist in his new comedy, Professor Beware!, gets an Egyptian eyeful in backstage theatre sequences from the picture, Lloyd is seen here surrounded by a bevy of Egyptian beauties, portrayed by Hollywood chorus girls in the film.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Inspecting a New Device - Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch, leading woman in Lloyd's current Paramount release, Professor, Beware!, try out a recent invention which enables a person to see positive film just as it would be shown on a projection film.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Sh-h! - the bloodhounds are on the trail! Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch enact a scene from their new comedy, Professor, Beware!, in which they are continually pursued by the police.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Elliott Nugent, and other cast members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus-- 10. Rehearsing the revival scene. Director Elliott Nugent, holding Lloyd, goes through action in hopes of adding humorous touches.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and a pedestrian on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd Meets a Namesake - while on location at Inyokern shooting scenes for Professor, Beware!, the comedian was introduced to Harold Lloyd Washmuth, a local lad named for Lloyd. According to the boy, his parents had some trouble deciding between the names of Babe Ruth, Gene Tunny, or Harold Lloyd.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and other cast members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus - 9. Back from the shades of Egypt, the Professor is given treatment by his excited rescuers. His human-interest story becomes a national subject for conversation due to newspaper notoriety, and he is started on his road to fame.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Fred Newmeyer on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Former Director Returns to the Fold - Fred Newmeyer, director of many of Harold Lloyd's most successful silent pictures, again works with the comedian, this time on the second unit of Professor, Beware!, current opus which Lloyd is producing for Paramount release. Newmeyer is seen here discussing progress on the picture with the comedian.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and crew members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus -- 1. Harold Lloyd, for a scene in his current comedy, Professor, Beware!, is required to lie quietly on the bottom of a sealed museum sarcophagus. The comedian plays an archeologist who experiments to determine how long a person could live while buried alive. He is seen here entering the outer coffin.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: It's a Dead Ringer - Harold Lloyd makes use of Egyptian atmosphere in his latest production, Professor, Beware! The statue, supposed to resemble the comedian, was made from a plaster cast of his features. Here he is seen inspecting the resemblance.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Lionel Stander, and Raymond Walburn in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea -- 2. Much of the action in Professor, Beware!, is of Lloyd's former thrill style. Here Lloyd, followed by Lionel Stander and Raymond Walburn, dashes for the yacht landing to escape the mob pursuing him for fancied insults.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea -- 8. Just before the battle. Harold Lloyd takes it east before going into another brawl with the sailors. The fight between landsmen and sailors is one of the picture's high spots.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Phyllis Welch, and Elliott Nugent on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Ladder of Fame - Harold Lloyd, whose current comedy is Professor, Beware! for Paramount, rests at the top of the comedy ladder of fame, while his new leading woman, Phyllis Welch, is on her way up. Director Elliott Nugent stands below and grins approval.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Spoils the Show-- Harold Lloyd, in an Egyptian tableau sequence from Professor, Beware!, comes up through a trap door in the stage and spoils the performance. Phyllis Welch, Lloyd's new leading woman, plays the lead in the tableau while the comedian himself is seen as an ambitious young professor of archeology.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Cleopatra and the Comedian -- Harold Lloyd, playing an ambitious young archeologist in his current comedy, Professor, Beware!, gets tangled up with reincarnation, Egyptian sacrophagi and tablets, and finally winds up on a cross-country chase from Los Angeles to New York. Phyllis Welch, the comedian's new leading woman, appears as an heiress in disguise who tries to crash the movies by way of an Egyptian tableau.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Dr. John A. Comstock preparing props for Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd Goes Egyptian -- 4. Dr. Comstock shoes the comedian and authentic sarcophagus of the Middle Kingdom. The mummy case in background is similar to one in which Lloyd is accidentally entombed in the comedy.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Lionel Stander, and crew members on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: 2. Harold Lloyd Swings into Action Again - many of the scene in Professor, Beware! are exteriors, since the story concerns an archeologist making a cross-country trip without money from Los Angeles to New York. Lloyd is seen here with Lionel Stander, who plays a friendly hobo in the picture, during an informal chat between scenes on a location at Kernville, Calif.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd goes Egyptian -- 7. Lloyd leaves no tablet unturned in his study of Egyptology. Here he compares glyphs on the prop tablet with impressions on the real fragment in the showcase.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Substitutes for Mummy - informal shot, taken on the Professor, Beware! set, catches Harold Lloyd rehearsing a scene in which he is almost suffocated after accidentally being left in an Egyptian sarcophagus. The sequence takes place in a Museum, where Lloyd is a young archeologist.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Elliott Nugent, and Archie Stout in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Conference On The Set - Harold Lloyd, noted comedian now producing Professor, Beware! for Paramount release, discusses with Elliott Nugent, director, and Archie Stout (left), cameraman, the action for his next scene. Lloyd plays a young museum archeologist in his new opus.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Elliott Nugent, and Archie Stout in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Seated on an Egyptian Sarcophagus - Harold Lloyd, shown here in an informal discussion with Director Elliott Nugent (left) and Cameraman Archie Stout, plays an archeologist in his current opus, Professor, Beware!. Much of the action takes place around an ancient sarcophagus in a museum.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Montagu Love, Christian Rub, and James Donaln in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Unusual Background for Comedy - much of Harold Lloyd's new comedy, Professor, Beware!, takes place in a museum setting. Lloyd plays a young archeologist. Seen here are Montagu Love (left) as the Museum head, Christian Rub, an attendant, and James Donlan, as a reporter.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, James Donlan, and Montagu Love in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Professor Tells All - Harold Lloyd, as a young professor of archeology in Professor, Beware!, narrates to a reporter (James Donlan) the love story of Neferus and Anebi, ancient Egyptians, whose romance is paralleled by that of the Professor. Montagu Love (left), as the Museum head, looks on in ill-concealed disapproval.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Comedian Takes a Bath -- 4. With an icy wind blowing across the bay, Lloyd stands, dripping and uncomfortable, on the float. In Professor, Beware!, the comedian goes through a thousand situations similar to the above in order to ensure typical laughs and thrills.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Archie Stout on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea -- 3. Before jumping into the chilly waters of the harbor, Lloyd goes into conference with Archie Stout, head cameraman, to determine camera lines and angles. Lloyd was forced to enter the water many times before the scene was finally given an OK.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Lionel Stander, Raymond Walburn, and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: False Alarm Firemen -- Lionel Stander, Raymond Walburn, and Harold Lloyd attempt to pose as firemen in order to gain access to a forbidden yacht in the harbor, but are stopped bu the captain. Lloyd's new comedy, Professor, Beware!, furnishes a laugh and a thrill a minute.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Elliot Nugent, cast members, and crew members in Porfessor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Just Before the Take - Harold Lloyd receives last minute instructions from director Elliott Nugent (right), as cameras record the number of the scene. The comedian's new picture in titled, Professor, Beware!

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, James Donlan, Christian Rub, Montagu Love, and another cast member in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus -- 6. Aided by prowling reporters and the museum director (Montagu Love), upper left, Rub finally removes the lid and discovers Lloyd, passed out cold with notebook and flashlight in hand. He attempted to take notes on his experiment.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Wild Ride on a Fire Engine -- for a scene in his latest picture, Professor, Beware!, Harold Lloyd turns in a false alarm in order to get rapid ride on a fire engine to his destination on the New York waterfront.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Fire, Fire! - cries Harold Lloyd, in this scene from Professor, Beware!, the comedian's current laugh-provoker. Lloyd turns in a false alarm in order to get a rapid ride through New York traffic.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: 3. Harold Lloyd swings into action again -- the comedian introduces a new leading lady to the screen in this picture. Phyllis Welch, seen here with Lloyd, is an importation from the New York stage, where she played in such hits as End of Summer, and High Tor. Her personality is best described as vivacious.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Candid Camera Sees Comedian - Harold Lloyd, in an offstage moment on the set of his new comedy, Professor, Beware!, perches high on a ladder to watch action. Phyllis Welch, newcomer to the screen, plays the feminine lead opposite Lloyd in his current opus.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and a crew member in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd, on location in the California hills shooting scenes for his new picture, Professor, Beware!, enjoys an early manicure on the set. The attractive manicurist is Lorraine L'Orange.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Harold Lloyd Has an Accident- but it's only for a scene in his current comedy, Professor, Beware! Lloyd appropriates a taxi in his rush to catch a boat in the New York harbor, and smashes it up.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Lionel Stander, Raymond Walburn, and Elliott Nugent in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea -- 6. Director Elliott Nugent (center) adds a touch of color to Raymond Walburn's costume as he places a fireman's hat on Walburn's head. Fire-engines enhance the impression of confusion in this dock sequence in Professor, Beware!

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, James Donlan, Christian Rub, Montagu Love, and Charles Lane in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comedian Entombed in Egyptian Sarcophagus -- 8. Gasping for breath, Lloyd, as the Professor, begins to revive. James Donlan (lower left) and Charles Lane (upper right), as the reporters, anxiously await the unusual story.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Cleopatra and the Comedian -- Harold Lloyd, playing an ambitious young archeologist in his current comedy, Professor, Beware!, gets tangled up with reincarnation, Egyptian sarcophagi and tablets, and finally winds up on a cross-country chase from Los Angeles to New York. Phyllis Welch, the comedian's new leading woman, appears as an heiress in disguise who tries to crash the movies by way of an Egyptian tableau.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Sh-h! - the bloodhounds are on the trail! Harold Lloyd and Phyllis Welch enact a scene from their new comedy, Professor, Beware!, in which they are continually pursued by the police.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and his family on the set of Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: First Family of Hollywood - relaxing between scenes for Professor, Beware! with his wife and daughters is Harold Lloyd. Mrs. Lloyd, formerly Mildred Davis, and the two children, Peggy and Gloria, often visit the comedian during his working hours.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd, Harold Lloyd Jr., and Dr. John A. Comstock preparing for Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Absorbed in the Distant Past -- Harold Lloyd, in company with his young son, Harold Jr., Learns from Dr. John A. Comstock, a director in the Los Angeles Museum, something of the science of preserving mummies in the Egyptian manner. Lloyd recently took his family on a tour of the museum in order to get authentic information for Egyptian sequences in his picture, Professor, Beware!

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and another cast member in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Movie Company Goes to Sea -- 9. Sailor, beware! When Harold Lloyd works up ambition he's a tough customer for anyone to handle. Professor, Beware! gives the comedian every opportunity to revert to his former thrill type of action.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and crew members in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Comedian Takes a Bath -- 1. Harold Lloyd, making scenes for Professor, Beware!, his current Paramount release demonstrates his willingness to do anything for a laugh. In freezing January weather, the comedian spent many hours in the chilly waters of Los Angeles Harbor to get scenes for the picture. Here he is seen awaiting the word action.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd and extras in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Professor Minus Pants - when a museum archeologist is taken to jail for going about in his shorts, it's news for the ever-present reporters. In Professor, Beware!, Harold Lloyd becomes the victim of circumstances and is apprehended on charges of immodesty.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harold Lloyd in Professor, Beware!
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Light Reading for the Professor - Harold Lloyd enacts the role of the sedate young professor of archeology in his current Paramount release, Professor, Beware!, the story of which takes him on a wild transcontinental chase. Here the comedian is seen staggering under a load of weighty volumes in keeping with his character.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Milton Frome and Red Skelton in Public Pigeon No. 1
Description.caption: PP-108PUBLIC PIGEON NO. 1UNIVERSAL-INTERNATIONAL'TIS FALSE...and wig and stunned performer give Rusty (Red Skelton) an idea which has hilarious results in RKO's "Public Pigeon No. 1," starring Skelton, Vivian Blaine and Janet Blair. The picture is a Universal-International release.

Title: Everett Glass, Colleen Miller, and Gene Barry in The Purple Mask
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:1782-11 THE PURPLE MASKUNIVERSAL-INTERNATIONALFrench Royalist agent Colleen Miller confers with a priest and a fellow agent in this scene from Universal-International's thrilling CinemaScope Technicolor melodrama, "The Purple Mask." Tony Curtis and Miss Miller are co-starred in the romantic leads.

Broadway playwright George S. Kaufman (R), made his Hollywood directorial debut with the filming of "The Senator Was Indiscreet" which also features Ella Raines, Arleen Whelan, Ray Collins, Allen Jenkins and introduces Peter Lind Hayes, Broadway and Hollywood nightclub favorite.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Randolph Scott with John Phillips and John Barradino in a scene from Seven Men From Now
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "Seven Men From Now" 1, (412-47)Ben Stride (Randolph Scott) is on the trail of seven dangerous outlaws. On a stormy night he is ambushed by Chiricahua Indians and his horse is killed. He continues on foot and spots the glow of a small campfire. Stride plods into the light of the fire. Two men squat by the blaze, drinking coffee. The suspicious pair, Jed (John Phillips) and Clint (John Barradino), realize they have been identified as two of the seven killers and go for their guns. Stride beats them to the draw.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Teresa Wright and Joseph Cotten in a scene from Shadow of a Doubt
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal Studios, Universal City, Calif."At first I didn't know you!" says Teresa Wright to her uncle, played by Joseph Cotten in a scene from Universal's "Shadow Of A Doubt," highly dramatic Thornton Wilder story being brought to the screen by Producer Jack H. Skirball. Teresa's exclamatory greeting doesn't hold good later in the story, however, for she is the one person who comes to know her famous uncle as a murderer. It's a film play full of suspense and is directed by that master of suspense, Alfred Hitchcock.

Radio Pictures.|~|Text From back of photograph: Comrades three in Walt Disney's most unique feature production, "So Dear To My Heart"--Jeremiah Kincaid (Bobby Driscoll), Tildy (Luana Patten) and Danny the Black Ram (himself). They raise a lot of hilarious excitement, hoart-tug and haunting recollections of an American era that has vanished in a homespun tale of mid-Indiana a generation ago. Others who share top honors in brilliant performances are Beulah Bondi, Burl Ives, Harry Carey, and Raymond Bond.

Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:From: Universal StudiosUniversal City, Calif.THE ADMIRAL WAS THE BEST MAN...This happy group very recently made news headlines with the first Hollywood glamor wedding of 1946. The happy bride and groom are at the right -- Film star Myrna Loy looking affectionately at her new mate Commodore Gene Markey. Appropriately enough, Mrs. Markey's new picture with Don Ameche is entitled, "So Goes My Love." The couple laughing at a bit of wedding witticism is Best Man Admiral William F. "Bull" Helsey, he of the sacred white horse and victorious Third Fleet, and Mrs. Collier Young, matron of honor.[REPEAT] This happy group very recently made news headlines with the first Hollywood glamor wedding of 1946. Name.subject: Marion, Charles R.
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Actress Elena Verdugo with husband Charles R. Marion in a publicity still for Song Of Scheherazade
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:From: Universal StudiosUniversal City, Calif.HOLLYWOOD NEWLYWEDSActress Elena Verdugo and screenwriter Charles Marion have had their troubles ever since he popped the question a few months back. Their marriage had to be postponed three times because Elena was working in Universal's "Song of Scheherazade." Finally they were married in March, when Charles suddenly was assigned to do a new script at Universal, where he is still at work. When and if their work allows them to have their honeymoon, they plan to go to Lake Tahoe, on the California-Nevada border, for six weeks before returning to the film capital.

Title: Glenn Leedy, James Baskett, and Bobby Driscoll in Song Of The South
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:UR-142 GOOD LISTENERS...James Baskett as Uncle Remus enchants Glenn Leedy and Bobby Driscoll with one of his fables in Walt Disney's delightful "Song of the South." Re-released by Buena Vista, the color by Technicolor production is based on Uncle Remus stories by Joel Chandler Harris."The Aristocats" feature length cartoon, and "Song of the South," live action cartoon, both Walt Disney Productions, open in a double bill Wednesday, June 27, in theatres and drive-ins throughout Los Angeles and Orange County.|~|WALT DISNEY'S"SONG OF THE SOUTH"Technicolor Re-released by Buena Vista Distribution Co., Inc.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Erik Rolf and Ruth Warrick in Song Of The South
Description.caption: WALT DISNEY'S"SONG OF THE SOUTH"Technicolor Re-released by Buena Vista Distribution Co., Inc.|~|Text from back of photograph:URAdv56: Two of the featured players in Walt Disney's first real-life photoplay, "Song of the South," an RKO Radio release, are Ruth Warrick and Eric Rolf. Rolf plays the role of a fighting southern newspaper editor, and Miss Warrick that of his wife, in the Technicolored Disney epic based on the beloved Uncle Remus stories by Joel Chandler Harris.

Title: Red Skelton and George Coulouris in A Southern Yankee
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:METRO-GOLDWYN-MAYERA Southern Yankee"A SOUTHERN YANKEE".....Red Skelton and Brian Donlevy are starred in this hilarious comedy where the laughs fly faster than the bullets, with Arlene Dahl in the feminine lead and George Coulouris featured in a strong supporting cast. Edward Sedgwick directed and Paul Jones produced for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.2. Later, delivering a newly-pressed uniform to the major's room, Aubrey accidentally discovers that Drumman really is the notorious Southern spy, "The Gray Spider." As Drumman is about to do away with him, Aubrey trips over a chair, his foot flies up and Dumman is caught flush on the chin and knocked unconscious. OPENS Tues Sept 21 FOX WILSHIRE, EGYPTIAN LOS ANGELES (downtown)

Title: Joel McCrea, Dean Stockwell, and Juano Hernandez in Stars In My Crown
Description.caption: M-G-M PICTORIAL REVIEW....."STARS IN MY CROWN"3. DISTURBING UNDERCURRENT: Parson Gray (Joel McCrea) comes upon John (Dean Stockwell) who with the help of Uncle Famous Prill (Juano Hernandez) is learning to fish. In fact, for generations Uncle Famous has taught most of the boys in Walesburg everything in relation to hunting, fishing and dogs. Now the Parson learns that Lon Beckett, owner of the general store, is demanding that Famous sell his plot of land because of a vein of mica which runs through it.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Spencer Tracy and Angela Lansbury in State Of The Union
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:STARS GET TOGETHER...Spencer Tracy and Angela Lansbury find plenty to talk about even when they aren't in front of the cameras for their scenes together in "Stat of the Union" in which they share stellar billing with Katharine Hepburn, Van Johnson, Adolphe Menjou and Lewis Stone. they are the romantic trouble-makers in the filmization of the Lindsay-Grouse Pulitzer Prize play. Frank Capra produced and directed the picture for Liberty Films. Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer releases the production.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Spencer Tracy in State Of The Union
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:THE PEOPLE'S CHOICE...Spencer Tracy, two-time Academy Award winner was literally "the people's choice" for the role of the presidential candidate in "State of the Union," Frank Capra's filmization of the Howard Lindsay-Russel Crouse Pulitzer Prize-winning play. Audiences will hold onto their hats when Tracy tosses his into the presidential ring in the romantic comedy which also stars Katherine Hepburn, Van Johnson, Angela Lansbury, Adolphe Menjou, and Louis Stone. He is the aircraft executive who see the White House out of one eye and ideals out of the other. Romantic and comedy situations in the Liberty Films production which Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer releases, finally have Tracy seeing straight -- ahead!METRO-GOLDWYN-MAYER

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Gene Tierney and Bruce Cabot in Sundown
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:(EXCLUSIVE)WANGER PHOTO by Donald Biddle KeyesGENE TIERNEY - BRUCE CABOTGene Tierney reaches independent stardom and Bruce Cabot plays the romantic male lead in Walter Wanger's spectacular African adventure, "Sundown", soon to be seen on the nation's screens. "Sundown" deals with the exciting experiences of six white men in an isolated colonial outpost along the Kenya-Abyssinia_Jubaland border in Central east Africa. Cabot is the British commissioner. Miss Tierney is Zia, supposedly half-caste daughter of a wealthy Arab trader, who returns to her home just as Shenzi tribesmen, given guns by enemy agents threaten the post as a challenge to British rule. "Sundown" is regarded as one of the the most colorful and distinctive action pictures in years; more suspenseful and arresting than Wanger's memorable 1940 hit, "Foreign Correspondent".

Title: Billy Gray, Nancy Reagan, and George Murphy in Talk About A Stranger
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:APPROVEDSEP 14 1951ADVERTISING COPY ADMINISTRATIONHOLLYWOODTHERE'S WORK TO BE DONE!.....George Murphy tells wife Nancy Davis and son Billy Gray that the frost threatening their orange crop will call for an all-night vigil with the smudge pots. Scene is from Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's "The Next Door Neighbor", heartwarming story about a boy who loses his dog. George Murphy, Nancy Davis, Lewis Stone, Kurt Kasznar and Billy Gray head the cast. David Bradley directed, Richard Goldstone produced from script by Margaret Fitts. Charlotte Armstrong wrote the original story.TALK ABOUT A STRANGER

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Ruby Dee and Paula Raymond in The Tall Target
Description.caption: DEATH UNDER THE WHEELS...Paula Raymond and Ruby Dee watch a man meet death beneath the wheels of a speeding train, in this thrilling moment from Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's historical mystery, "The Tall Target." The cast is headed by Dick Powell, Miss Raymond, Adolphe Menjou, and Marshall Thompson. Film was directed by Anthony Mann and produced by Richard Goldstone. George W. Yates and Art Cohn wrote the screen play.

Name.subject: Aumont, Jean Pierre
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Maria Montez with her husband Jean Pierre Aumont in a promotional photo for Tangier
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:Universal StudioUniversal City, Calif.A MOVIE STAR COUNTS HER BLESSINGSMaria Montez has much to be thankful for this Thanksgiving season. Home from France has come Jean Pierre Aumont, her actor-husband who served as a De Gaulleist attach to General Eisenhower's staff. This will be Maria's first Thanksgiving with him in three years. They're thankful, too, because the stork is heading their way, scheduled to arrive in March. Currently, Miss Montez is rushing Universal's "Tangier" to completion.Maria Montez has much to be thankful for this Thanksgiving season. Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:LOVE ON A BUS -----5) This is the start of the pucker. Milland looks grim, Miss Wright is ready.(PLEASE CREDIT "THE TROUBLE WITH WOMEN")

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Teresa Wright and Ray Milland in The Trouble With Women
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:LOVE ON A BUS -----Love on a bus should be easy for a young professor who believes in the subjugation of women - and in this sequence from Paramount's new comedy sensation, "The Trouble With Women", Professor Ray Milland has little trouble in reaching an osculatory agreement with Teresa Wright. Miss Wright plays a reporter and Brian Donlevy her city editor in this gay photoplay in which Milland, author of a tome on male domination, is taken for a ride in more than one sense. This sequence takes place atop a Fifth Avenue double-decker.1) Professor Ray Milland's faith in his theory of subjugation of women begins to waiver as Miss Wright flashes a melting glance his way.(PLEASE CREDIT "THE TROUBLE WITH WOMEN")

Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:LOVE ON A BUS -----6) Approach completed, osculation accomplished - but Miss Wright looks at the camera as Ray goes to work!(PLEASE CREDIT "THE TROUBLE WITH WOMEN")

Title: Teresa Wright and Ray Milland in The Trouble With Women
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:LOVE ON A BUS -----3) Well, she didn't slap my face, reasons the professor. Next objective: setting up for the clinch.(PLEASE CREDIT "THE TROUBLE WITH WOMEN")

Name.actor: Evans, Joan|~|Symons, Marylin|~|Elmore, Dick|~|Carroll, Mildred|~|Eskew, Carmelita|~|Whitney, Joan|~|Thomas, Beverly|~|Buchanan, Shirley|~|Worthington, Barbara|~|Jordan, Joan|~|Crosby, Bob, $d 1913-1993
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Barbara Worthington, Marylin Symons, Carmelita Eskew, Dick Elmore, Bob Crosby, and others in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-116--NICE LINES...Bob Crosby checks script with some of the talent for his television show in RKO Radio's lavishly gay Technicolor filmusical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Bob plays the star-producer who gives Tony Martin, Janet Leigh, Ann Miller, Gloria DeHaven and Barbara Lawrence their big chance. Left to right here--back row: Barbara Worthington, Marilyn Symons, Carmelita Eskew, Dick Elmore, Crosby, Joan Jordan, Joan Whitney, Shirley Buchanan. Bottom row: Joan Evans, Beverly Thomas, Mildred Carroll.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Charlie Dale, Joe Smith, and Eddie Bracken in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-85--BILLS, and no money to pay them, brings that distressed expression to Eddie Bracken's face. Charlie Dale and Joe Smith (Smith and Dale) are the bad-news boys in this scene from "Two Tickets to Broadway," RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical about the tribulations of show business.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken and Gloria DeHaven in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-161--TRAPPED--Eddie Bracken fails to escape from the jealous guarding of girl friend Gloria DeHaven in this scene from RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." The two carry on a comedy romance that is secondary to the love interest centering around Tony Martin and Janet Leigh.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh and Tony Martin in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-156--DREAM OF LOVE - Janet Leigh and Tony Martin as they appear in the starting phase of the spectacular dream ballet which provides one of the climaxes of RKO Radio's Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Janet hears Tony singing in her dreams, and still dreaming, rises to dance.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Bob Crosby in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-138--THE CROSBY BOYS, Bob (left) and Bing (in effigy), do a number for RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical, Two Tickets to Broadway." Bob does all of the singing, a Sammy Cahn number called "Let's Make Comparisons," while Bing's dummy just stands there and takes it.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Bob Crosby and John Gallaudet on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-139--TELEVISION comes to the movies in this scene from RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Bob Crosby, who plays the producer-star of a TV show, is walking off stage with John Gallaudot, who portrays his production manager.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Director James V. Kern with Bob Crosby and John Gallaudet on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-135--JAMES V. KERN (in tweed coat) steps before the cameras to do a bit with Bob Crosby and John Gallaudet in a television act scene for "Two Tickets to Broadway," RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical about show business.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-126--THE BUM'S RUSH and a canine kiss are Eddie Bracken's reward for trying to crash Bob Crosby's television studio in this scene from RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh rehearsing with dancer Marge Champion for Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:Two Tickets To BroadwayJanet LeighMarge Champion

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Gloria DeHaven, Charlie Dale, Joe Smith, and Eddie Bracken in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-112--HOLD EVERYTHING!--Eddie Bracken shouts the glad tidings to Gloria DeHaven - that she's about to go on television. The unhappy skeptics in this scene from RKO Radio's scintillating Technicolor filmusical, "Two Tickets to Broadway," are Charlie Dale and Joe Smith, the famed Smith and Dale comedy team.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Tony Martin, Eddie Bracken, Charlie Dale, and Joe Smith in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-32--CLOSE HARMONY...Tony Martin, Eddie Bracken, Charlie Dale and Joe Smith (Smith and Dale) are one for all and all for one in this scene of RKO Radio's colorful Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." They've formed a partnership to stage the show that will make Tony famous and all of them rich.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken and Tony Martin in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-27--SURPRISE....Tony Martin opens what he thinks is his suitcase, and draws a surprise for himself and Eddie Bracken in this bit of action from RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical "Two Tickets to Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: John Gallaudet, Eddie Bracken, and Tony Martin in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-136--FALL GUY--Eddie Bracken is in trouble, or making it, as usual in this scene with Tony Martin and John Gallaudet (left) for RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Evelyn Lovequist, Joan Jordan, Tony Martin, and Eddie Bracken in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-132--THE PLOT THICKENS--Tony Martin and Eddie Bracken, disguised with whiskers and cheaters, do some dark plotting in this scene for RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Showgirls Evelyn Lovequist and Joan Jordan in background.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Tony Martin and Eddie Bracken on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Pub-A73--CAKES AND COFFEE are what Tony Martin and Eddie Bracken are supposed to have to scramble for in RKO Radio's Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." But it's plentiful pickings here, between scenes, in a delicatessen setting

Name.subject: Silvers, Sid, $d 1901-1976
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Screenwriter Sid Silvers and director James V. Kern on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Pub-A72--RIGGING THE DUMMY--Director James V. Kern (right) tells Makeup Man Jimmy House to add a few more touches to the effigy of Bing Crosby which is featured in a Bob Crosby number for RKO Radio's Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Screen writer Sid Silvers (left) looks on critically.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh, Tony Martin, and director James V. Kern on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Pub-A48--BETWEEN SCENES CONFERENCE--Janet Leigh, Tony Martin and Director James V. Kern discuss forthcoming action of "Two Tickets to Broadway," RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical about show business.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh eating lunch with husband Tony Curtis during filming of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTwo Tickets to BroadwayLeigh-Curtis

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photographPHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Pub-A34 - HAM FROM HAMLET - Eddie Bracken slices it between scenes of RKO Radio's gay Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway," when he chances upon a theatrical poster advertising a London production of the Shakespearean classic.

Name.subject: McGonigle, George
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Property man George McGonigle with Ann Miller and Barbara Lawrence on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Pub-A33 - FINGER BOWL SERVICE is provided Ann Miller and Barbara Lawrence by Property Man George McGonigle after the two stars have enjoyed a feast of cold fried chicken for scenes of "Two Tickets to Broadway," RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical.

Name.subject: Cronjager, Eddie, $d 1904-1960
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken and Gloria DeHaven with director James V. Kern and cinematographer Eddie Cronjager on the set of Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-PUB-A27--"HIT HIM AGAIN, HARDER!", Director James Kern tells Gloria DeHaven how he wants her to step on the already flattened Eddie Bracken in a comedy scene for RKO Radio's "Two Tickets to Broadway." Cinematographer Eddie Cronjager is the somber-faced individual in the background. He's figuring out how to light the massacre to best Technicolor advantage.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh rehearsing with dancer Marge Champion for Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:TTB-Pub-A14 & 19---NEAT FORM is displayed by Janet Leigh as she rehearses with Marge Champion. In preparation for her starring role in RKO Radio's big Technicolor musical "Two Tickets to Broadway," Miss Leigh worked many hours with the famed dancers Marge and Gower Champion.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Leigh rehearsing for Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:TTB-PUB-A11, A18 WONDERFUL FORM is displayed by Janet Leigh as she does her dancing exercise in preparation for her starring role in the lavish RKO Radio Technicolor musical "Two Tickets to Broadway." Miss Leigh will be seen as a girl from a small town who makes good on Broadway in a brilliant cast which includes Tony Martin, Eddie Bracken, Ann Miller, Gloria DeHaven, Barbara Lawrence, Smith and Dale and Bob Crosby

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Eddie Bracken, Charlie Dale, Joe Smith, and Tony Martin in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-31--A TOAST to fame or bankruptcy is proposed by Eddie Bracken while Charlie Dale and Joe Smith (Smith and Dale) and Tony Martin wonder which it will be, a scene from RKO Radio's brilliant Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Tony Martin, Eddie Bracken, Charlie Dale, and Joe Smith in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-30--SALES TALK...Tony Martin and Eddie Bracken tell Charlie Dale and Joe Smith (Smith and Dale) what a killing they can make by backing Tony's television show, a scene from RKO Radio's big Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Gloria DeHaven and Eddie Bracken in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-22--ON THE BRINK of disaster is Eddie Bracken in this scene with Gloria DeHaven for RKO Radio's brilliant Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Gloria plays Eddie's long suffering girl friend, and she has just found out that he has double crossed her once again.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Joe Smith and Charlie Dale in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Adv. 1 to 6 inc. -- SMITH AND ALE [sp], comedy headliners since the turn of the century, bring their inimitable brand of fun to the screen in RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Joe Smith (left) and Charlie Dale are seen as delicatessen owners who disagree about backing Tony Martin and his four girl friends, Janet Leigh, Ann Miller, Gloria DeHaven and Barbara Lawrence, in a show but finally emerge as the angels.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Joe Smith and Charlie Dale in Two Tickets To Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:PHOTO BY GASTON LONGETTTB-Adv. 1 to 6 inc. -- SMITH AND ALE [sp], comedy headliners since the turn of the century, bring their inimitable brand of fun to the screen in RKO Radio's lavish Technicolor musical, "Two Tickets to Broadway." Joe Smith (left) and Charlie Dale are seen as delicatessen owners who disagree about backing Tony Martin and his four girl friends, Janet Leigh, Ann Miller, Gloria DeHaven and Barbara Lawrence, in a show but finally emerge as the angels.

Title: Katharine Hepburn and Robert Taylor in Undercurrent
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:MARITAL TRIANGLE.....The shadowy presence of another man disrupts the marriage bliss of Katharine Hepburn and Robert Taylor in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's suspenseful romance, "Undercurrent". The marital ties of the couple are insidiously and slowly torn apart by a man who unconsciously dooms their love. Taylor, in his first postwar picture after three years in the Navy, co-stars with Miss Hepburn, supported by Robert Mitchum, Edmund Gwenn and Marjorie Main. Vincente Minnelli directed. Pandro S. Berman produced.
