Title: Irene Dunne and Walter Catlett on the set of Unfinished Business
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:OFFICE SCENE A BUSY ONE FOR FILM COMEDIANIrene Dunne rehearses a scene with Walter Catlett for Universal's comedy-drama, "UNFINISHED BUSINESS," which found Catlett carrying on about a dozen activities at once. The scene is one in which Miss Dunne, as an aspiring singer, auditions for a New York night club manager, portrayed by Catlett. While Miss Dunne sings, Catlett carries on telephone conversations, dictates, has manicure and shoe shine, and performs other activities.Produced and directed by Gregory La Cava, the new film presents Miss Dunne as a small-town girl who comes to New York, falls in love with a wealthy man-of-the-world (Preston Foster) but marries his brother (Robert Montgomery).

Title: David Wayne and Tom Ewell in Up Front
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:From: Universal-InternationalUniversal City, Calif.WILLIE & JOE MOVE "UP FRONT" IN THE MOVIES"You'll get over it, Joe. Oncet [sp] I wuz gonna write a book exposing the army after the war myself."Tom Ewell (right) and David Wayne in the title roles of "Up Front," Universal-International's comedy film based on the Bill Mauldin cartoon G.I.s, bring the screen something new in the way of comedy. While soldiers and soldiering have been the butts of self-inflicted comedy barbs since the beginning of time, it remained for Mauldin to point up the gripe of the "dogface" so that all could understand and appreciate him - - excepting "the brass," of course. the movie brings cartoon situations and dialogue to the screen bodily.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: David Wayne and Tom Ewell in Up Front
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:From: Universal-InternationalUniversal City, Calif."UP FRONT" WITH WILLIE AND JOE - IN THE MOVIES"Willie, yesterday ya saved my life an' I swore I'd pay ya back. Here's my last pair of dry socks."A memorable comedy situation, one of many such to be seen in the film, comes to life in "Up Front," the movie based on the Bill Mauldin World War II cartoon. Played by Tom Ewell (right) and David Wayne, Willie and Joe bring to the screen the delightfully caustic-comic viewpoint of the citizen-soldier as inimicably expressed by Mauldin's "dogfaces." "Up Front" features Marina Berti, an Italian beauty, Jeffrey Lynn and Richard Egan with Ewell and Wayne."Willie, yesterday ya saved my life an' I swore I'd pay ya back. Here's my last pair of dry socks."A memorable comedy situation, one of many such to be seen in the film, comes to life in "Up Front," the movie based on the Bill Mauldin World War II cartoon. Played by Tom Ewell (right) and David Wayne, Willie and Joe bring to the screen the delightfully caustic-comic viewpoint of the citizen-soldier as inimicably expressed by Mauldin's "dogfaces." "Up Front" features Marina Berti, an Italian beauty, Jeffrey Lynn and Richard Egan with Ewell and Wayne.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: David Wayne and Tom Ewell in Up Front
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:From: Universal-InternationalUniversal City, Calif."UP FRONT" COMES TO THE SCREENThe Movies Discover the "Dogfaces," Willie & JoeFunniest by-product of World War II was the "dogface," the lowly G.I. whose beefing typifies the democratic civilian-soldier at war. When Bill Mauldin, soldier-cartoonist, personified the "dogface" in the unforgettable Willie and Joe in newspapers and in his book, "Up Front," it was only a question of time until that book reached the screen. After a wide search for actors who would not only look like Willie and Joe, but who could present them in the underplayed, undramatic way of the Mauldin originals, Universal-International has completed "Up Front" starring David Wayne and Tom Ewell. Here they are as seen in the film, borrowing situations and dialogue from the Mauldin cartoons:4 "...so Archibald kissed her agin an' gently put her head on th' pillow. She gazed at him wit' half-shut eyes--tremblin' hard--don't forget to buy next week's installment at yer newsstand."4 "...so Archibald kissed her agin an' gently put her head on th' pillow. She gazed at him wit' half-shut eyes--tremblin' hard--don't forget to buy next week's installment at yer newsstand."

Title: Helen Tamiris Dancers performing a number in Up In Central Park
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal-International, Universal City, California; "Up In Central Park" -- A Pictorial Synopsis; "Up In Central Park" in Universal-International's musical starring Deanne Durbin, Dick Haymes and Vincent Price, is the film adaptation of the stage hit that ran 15 months on Broadway. The movie features music from the New York production, plus a new song by Sigmund Romberg and Dorothy Fields. Dance director Helen Tamiris was brought to Hollywood to stage the choreography. Produced and written for the screen by Karl Tunberg, the movie was directed by William Seiter. The story in pictures: 6. The Currier and Ives prints and stereopticon views are brought to life on the screen by the famed Helen Tamiris Dancers, favorite Broadway protagonists of the American ballet.

Title: Anna Neagle in Victoria The Great
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph:Lovely Anna Neagle affords winsome evidence that Hollywood has no corner on the beauty market. One of England's foremost actresses, Miss Neagle promises to win a large American following with her brilliant portrayal of the title role in RKO Radio's "Victoria The Great."

Title: Jean Peters and Anthony Quinn in Viva Zapata
Description.caption: A scene from the Twentieth Century-Fox production"VIVA ZAPATA"Text from back of photograph:Anthony QUINN fait une pittoresque creation dans le role d'Eufemio, frre d'Emiliano Zapata (Marlon BRANDO). General victorieux, Eufemio veut profiter de "sa" victoire mais Emiliano le lui permettra pas. "VIVA ZAPATA", produit personnellement par Darryl F. ZANUCK, realize par Elia KAZAN, ecrit par John STEINBECK, est un film 20th CENTURY-FOX.
